Accidental release prevention and emergency response policies:
Operating in a safe and responsible manner is a core value and an integral part of CF Industries. Our safety strategy revolves around our "Do It Right" value and permeates our business in three key ways:
-	Robust systems that provide a clear, repeatable direction toward excellence.
-	Superior performance that aligns effective and efficient EHS activities with operations.
-	Engaged culture that empowers consistent behaviors that drive toward excellence.

CF Industries works closely with emergency responders and other local officials to develop detailed emergency response plans that extend beyond our physical operating locations.

Mt. Vernon Terminal and the regulated substances handled:
Mt. Vernon Terminal stores and distributes anhydrous ammonia. The regulated substances, as defined by 40 CFR Part 68, which are present at the facility in more than the threshold quantity are anhydrous ammonia.

The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps:
The Mt. Vernon Terminal has taken all the necessary steps to comply with all of the accidental release and chemical-specific prevention requirements as set forth in U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) 40 CFR Part 68. This facility is also subject to the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Process Safety Management (PSM) standard 29 CFR 1910.119. The following summarizes the elements of the release and chemical-specific prevention that are in place at our facility:
-	Process safety information that is accurate and up to date;
-	Well-trained operating, maintenance, and contract personnel;
-	Written operating procedures;
-	Mechanical integrity procedures for process equipment inspections and quality control;
-	Management of change and pre-startup safety review procedures;
-	Periodic, detailed Process Hazard Analysis by a team of qualified personnel with subject matter expertise;
-	P

eriodic audits of the PSM and RMP;
-	Employee participation;
-	Employee training and continuing education;
-	Incident investigation procedures;
-	Hot work permitting verifying the implementation of fire prevention and protection requirements prior to the beginning of hot work operations;
-	Coordination with local emergency and fire responders;
-	Stringent design standards of equipment which incorporate substantial safety factors and include state of the art monitoring and control instrumentation; and
-	Formal policies for contractor management.

This facility is also a participant in the Occupational Health and Safety Administration's (OSHA) Voluntary Protection Program (VPP) to promote effective worksite-based safety and health and have qualified for VPP Star status, which is recognition for exemplary achievement in the prevention and control of occupational safety and health hazards and the development, implementation and continuous improvement of safety and health management systems. Approval into VPP is OSHA's official recognition of the outstanding efforts of employers and employees who have achieved exemplary occupational safety and health.

The five-year accident history:
This facility has not had any accidental releases subject to EPA 40 CFR Part 68, within the last five years. 

